That’s the right question.
If “integrity” isn’t anchored, it becomes just a feeling—and feelings shift.

The tricky part: it’s not entirely “whatever you want.”
If it were, integrity would collapse into rationalization.

There are really two layers:

⸻

1) Personal Integrity (your chosen standard)

This is where you do decide.

It’s your:

* priorities
* goals
* identity
* what kind of life you want to build

Example:

* “I show up for my family”
* “I build things that matter”
* “I don’t quit when it gets hard”

This is flexible and personal.

⸻

2) Structural Integrity (constraints you don’t get to ignore)

This is where people get it wrong.

Some things aren’t optional if you want trust, stability, or reality to cooperate:

* Truth matters → if you bend it, things break
* Cause and effect is real → actions have consequences
* Other people exist → harm and trust are not subjective

You don’t have to believe these—but if you ignore them, the system pushes back.

⸻

So what is integrity “to”?

The cleanest answer:

Integrity = alignment between your actions and
(a) your chosen values
AND
(b) reality’s constraints

⸻

Why this matters for you specifically

If your internal state shifts (like you mentioned), then:

* Personal values give you direction
* Structural constraints give you stability

Without (a) → you drift
Without (b) → you delude yourself

⸻

A tight version you can actually use

Pick 3–5 anchors that survive any state you’re in.

For example:

* I don’t lie to myself
* I don’t intentionally harm people
* I follow through or I renegotiate
* I build more than I destroy

That’s it.

Not 100 rules. Just load-bearing beams.

⸻

Final cut

You’re right that people choose their level—but not freely.

They’re always negotiating between:

* what they want
* what works

And integrity is the bridge.

⸻

If you want it distilled into one line:

Integrity isn’t loyalty to a self.
It’s loyalty to what still holds when you’re not stable.